ile Buddhism’s disappearance in eastern India was a slow and gradual process, the Buddhist book-cult played an important role in sustaining its identity. In addition, by examining the physical traces left by later Nepalese users and the contemporary ritual use of the book in Nepal, Kim shows how human agency was critical in perpetuating and intensifying the potency of a manuscript as a sacred object throughout time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBooksxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aBuddhismzSouth AsiaxRitualsxHistory. 0aBuddhist illumination of books and manuscriptszSouth AsiaxHistory. 0aManuscripts, SanskritzSouth AsiaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aancient art.  aanthropology.  aart.  aartists.  aasian.  abeauty.  abuddhism.  abuddhist imagery.  abuddhist manuscripts.  abuddhist temples.  abuddhist.  acultic innovation.  acultural history.  adivine presence.  aeastern india.  aengaging.  ahistorical analysis.  ahistorical.  aillustrated manuscripts.  aindian practitioners.  amedieval illustrated buddhist manuscripts.  apaintings.  apatronage.  areligion.  areligious texts.  areligious.  asacred objects.  asacred space.  asocial science.  asouth asian buddhist book cult.  aspiritual transformation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027386340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095488540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954885/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d